-- Targeted migration: standardize SAA-C03-P% to official 65q spec.
-- 1) Bump questionCount to 65 on P1..P4 (P5, P6 already 65).
-- 2) Insert 6 grounded fill questions across under-served domains.
-- Does NOT touch published/deletedAt or any other field.
-- Idempotent: WHERE filters skip rows already at target; INSERTs guarded by WHERE NOT EXISTS.

CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgcrypto;

-- 1) Standardize questionCount
UPDATE "Exam" SET "questionCount" = 65
  WHERE code LIKE 'SAA-C03-P%' AND "questionCount" <> 65;

-- 2) Insert grounded fill questions
-- SAA-C03-P1: 1 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer at a financial services company needs to ensure that all objects uploaded to an Amazon S3 bucket containing sensitive customer data are encrypted using keys managed by AWS KMS, and that the encryption keys are automatically rotated on an annual basis. The engineer also wants to ensure that all API calls related to key usage are logged for compliance auditing. Which combination of actions will meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable SSE-KMS on the S3 bucket using a customer-managed key (CMK), enable automatic key rotation on the CMK, and enable AWS CloudTrail in the account."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable SSE-S3 on the S3 bucket, create a custom Lambda function to rotate the encryption key every 365 days, and enable AWS CloudTrail in the account."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable SSE-C on the S3 bucket, store the customer-provided key in AWS Secrets Manager with an annual rotation schedule, and use Amazon Macie to audit key usage."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable DSSE-KMS on the S3 bucket using an AWS managed key, rely on AWS CloudTrail for auditing, and manually rotate the key annually using the AWS Management Console."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct because it directly satisfies all three requirements with the least operational overhead. As stated in the source material, SSE-KMS uses customer-managed keys (CMKs) stored in AWS KMS, and 'automatic key rotation (annual for symmetric CMKs)' is a built-in KMS feature that can be enabled with a single toggle — no custom code required. Additionally, 'CloudTrail: audit log of all API calls; required for security/compliance forensics' captures every KMS API call (Decrypt, GenerateDataKey, etc.) automatically once enabled. Option B is incorrect because SSE-S3 (AES-256) uses AWS-managed keys entirely controlled by AWS and does not use CMKs, so the engineer cannot control or audit key usage at the KMS level; furthermore, building a custom Lambda rotation function adds unnecessary operational overhead. Option C is incorrect because SSE-C requires the client to supply and manage the raw key material on every request; while Secrets Manager can store and rotate the key, the engineer bears full responsibility for key delivery and there is no native KMS audit trail for SSE-C key usage — Amazon Macie discovers sensitive data in S3, not key usage logs. Option D is incorrect because AWS managed keys (aws/s3) do not support customer-controlled rotation schedules or key policies, giving the engineer no administrative control, and manual rotation defeats the requirement for automatic rotation.$patch$, $patch$Design Secure Architectures$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kms/latest/developerguide/rotate-keys.html","label":"AWS KMS – Rotating AWS KMS keys"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/UsingKMSEncryption.html","label":"Amazon S3 – Protecting data using server-side encryption with AWS KMS keys (SSE-KMS)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kms/latest/developerguide/logging-using-cloudtrail.html","label":"AWS CloudTrail – Logging AWS KMS API calls"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SAA-C03-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer at a financial services company needs to ensure that all objects uploaded to an Amazon S3 bucket containing sensitive customer data are encrypted using keys managed by AWS KMS, and that the encryption keys are automatically rotated on an annual basis. The engineer also wants to ensure that all API calls related to key usage are logged for compliance auditing. Which combination of actions will meet these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);

-- SAA-C03-P2: 1 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer is designing an architecture where an EC2 instance in a private subnet must retrieve sensitive database credentials at runtime without storing them in the application code or environment variables. The credentials must be automatically rotated every 30 days. Which combination of AWS services best satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Store credentials in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store (Standard tier) as plaintext parameters and retrieve them via the EC2 instance metadata service."},{"id":"b","text":"Store credentials in AWS Secrets Manager with automatic rotation enabled via a Lambda function, and grant the EC2 instance access through an IAM role attached to the instance."},{"id":"c","text":"Store credentials in an Amazon S3 bucket with SSE-S3 encryption, restrict access using a bucket policy, and have the EC2 instance download the credentials file at startup."},{"id":"d","text":"Hardcode the credentials in the EC2 user data script and encrypt the EBS root volume with an AWS KMS customer-managed key (CMK)."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that 'AWS Secrets Manager auto-rotates secrets via Lambda; integrates with RDS/Aurora/Redshift natively.' This directly satisfies the 30-day rotation requirement without manual intervention. Attaching an IAM role to the EC2 instance (per the 'IAM roles for EC2' principle and least-privilege guidance in the source) allows the instance to call Secrets Manager APIs using temporary credentials obtained via STS — no static credentials ever exist in code or environment variables.

Option A is incorrect: Parameter Store Standard tier does not natively support automatic secret rotation, and storing credentials as plaintext violates secure-credential handling.

Option C is incorrect: Downloading credentials from S3 at startup does not provide automatic rotation every 30 days, and the file would still be exposed in the instance's filesystem after download.

Option D is incorrect: Hardcoding credentials in user data is a critical security anti-pattern — user data is accessible in plaintext via the EC2 metadata service to any process running on the instance. Encrypting the EBS volume with a CMK does not mitigate this exposure, as the running OS decrypts the volume transparently.$patch$, $patch$Design Secure Architectures$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/rotating-secrets.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – Rotate secrets automatically"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/id_roles_use_switch-role-ec2.html","label":"AWS IAM – Using IAM roles for Amazon EC2"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/auth-and-access.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – How Secrets Manager works with IAM"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SAA-C03-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer is designing an architecture where an EC2 instance in a private subnet must retrieve sensitive database credentials at runtime without storing them in the application code or environment variables. The credentials must be automatically rotated every 30 days. Which combination of AWS services best satisfies these requirements?$patch$);

-- SAA-C03-P3: 2 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer at a financial services company needs to ensure that all objects uploaded to an Amazon S3 bucket containing sensitive customer PII are encrypted using AWS KMS customer-managed keys (CMKs). The engineer also wants AWS to automatically rotate the encryption keys annually without any manual intervention. Which S3 server-side encryption option, combined with which KMS key configuration, satisfies BOTH requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use SSE-S3 (AES-256) with an AWS-managed key; enable automatic key rotation in the S3 console."},{"id":"b","text":"Use SSE-KMS with a customer-managed CMK (symmetric); enable automatic key rotation on the CMK in AWS KMS."},{"id":"c","text":"Use SSE-C with a customer-provided key; store the key in AWS Secrets Manager and rotate it annually via a Lambda function."},{"id":"d","text":"Use DSSE-KMS with an AWS-managed key; automatic key rotation is handled entirely by S3 with no KMS configuration required."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'SSE-KMS' uses AWS KMS for encryption, and 'automatic key rotation (annual for symmetric CMKs)' is supported for customer-managed keys (CMKs). By selecting SSE-KMS on the S3 bucket and pointing it to a symmetric customer-managed CMK with automatic rotation enabled in KMS, both requirements are met — the customer retains full control over the CMK (audit, policy, grants) and AWS KMS automatically rotates it every year. 

Option A is incorrect because SSE-S3 uses AES-256 with AWS-managed keys (not customer-managed CMKs), giving the customer no direct KMS key control, and S3 does not expose a separate key rotation toggle for SSE-S3. 

Option C is incorrect because SSE-C requires the client to supply the raw encryption key with every request; the key is never stored or managed by KMS, and Secrets Manager rotation via Lambda addresses secret storage — not the S3 encryption mechanism itself. 

Option D is incorrect because DSSE-KMS (dual-layer SSE with KMS) does use KMS, but the claim that 'automatic rotation is handled entirely by S3 with no KMS configuration required' is false — key rotation must still be enabled on the CMK in KMS, and selecting an AWS-managed key would remove direct customer control over the CMK, violating the customer-managed key requirement.$patch$, $patch$Design Secure Architectures$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kms/latest/developerguide/rotate-keys.html","label":"AWS KMS – Rotating AWS KMS keys"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/serv-side-encryption.html","label":"Amazon S3 – Protecting data with server-side encryption"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/UsingKMSEncryption.html","label":"Amazon S3 – Using SSE-KMS encryption for cross-account operations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SAA-C03-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer at a financial services company needs to ensure that all objects uploaded to an Amazon S3 bucket containing sensitive customer PII are encrypted using AWS KMS customer-managed keys (CMKs). The engineer also wants AWS to automatically rotate the encryption keys annually without any manual intervention. Which S3 server-side encryption option, combined with which KMS key configuration, satisfies BOTH requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a globally distributed e-commerce application backed by Amazon DynamoDB. During flash sales, read traffic spikes to millions of requests per second, causing latency to degrade from single-digit milliseconds to tens of milliseconds. The development team needs to reduce read latency to microsecond levels without re-architecting the application's data model or changing DynamoDB table configurations. Which solution BEST meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) and update the application to use the DAX cluster endpoint instead of the DynamoDB endpoint."},{"id":"b","text":"Place an Amazon ElastiCache for Redis cluster in front of DynamoDB and implement a cache-aside (lazy loading) pattern in the application."},{"id":"c","text":"Add Global Secondary Indexes (GSIs) on the most frequently queried attributes to speed up read operations."},{"id":"d","text":"Switch the DynamoDB table from provisioned capacity mode to on-demand capacity mode to automatically handle traffic spikes."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that 'DAX (in-memory accelerator) for microsecond reads' is the purpose-built solution for accelerating DynamoDB reads to microsecond latency. DAX is a fully managed, DynamoDB-compatible in-memory cache that sits transparently in front of DynamoDB. Because DAX exposes the same API as DynamoDB, the application only needs to point to the DAX cluster endpoint — the data model and table configuration remain unchanged, satisfying the constraint. Option B (ElastiCache with cache-aside) could reduce latency but requires more significant application changes to implement the caching logic and does not achieve microsecond latency as reliably as DAX's tight DynamoDB integration. Option C (adding GSIs) improves query flexibility and can speed up specific access patterns, but GSIs do not reduce read latency to microseconds — they still hit DynamoDB storage. Option D (on-demand capacity) prevents throttling during spikes but does not reduce read latency; it only affects throughput scaling.$patch$, $patch$Design High-Performing Architectures$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/DAX.html","label":"Amazon DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) – Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/DAX.concepts.html","label":"DAX: How It Works"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/best-practices.html","label":"Choosing the Right DynamoDB Read Strategy"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SAA-C03-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company runs a globally distributed e-commerce application backed by Amazon DynamoDB. During flash sales, read traffic spikes to millions of requests per second, causing latency to degrade from single-digit milliseconds to tens of milliseconds. The development team needs to reduce read latency to microsecond levels without re-architecting the application's data model or changing DynamoDB table configurations. Which solution BEST meets this requirement?$patch$);

-- SAA-C03-P4: 2 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A solutions architect is designing a data processing pipeline where an EC2 instance in a private subnet must read objects from an Amazon S3 bucket. The security team requires that no S3 traffic traverse the public internet and that all access be restricted to only this specific S3 bucket. Which combination of actions satisfies these requirements? (Select ONE)$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Attach a NAT Gateway to the private subnet's route table and configure an S3 bucket policy that restricts access to the NAT Gateway's Elastic IP address."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a Gateway VPC endpoint for Amazon S3, update the private subnet's route table to direct S3 traffic through the endpoint, and attach an endpoint policy that restricts access to only the specific S3 bucket ARN."},{"id":"c","text":"Create an Interface VPC endpoint for Amazon S3 using AWS PrivateLink, and attach a security group rule allowing HTTPS traffic from the EC2 instance's security group to the interface endpoint."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration on the bucket and configure the EC2 instance to use the Transfer Acceleration endpoint, which automatically keeps traffic within the AWS network."},{"id":"e","text":"Deploy a proxy EC2 instance in a public subnet with an Elastic IP, configure the private EC2 instance to route S3 requests through the proxy, and restrict the S3 bucket policy to the proxy's Elastic IP."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that 'VPC endpoints (Gateway for S3/DynamoDB, Interface via PrivateLink for other services) keep traffic on AWS backbone.' A Gateway VPC endpoint for S3 is the purpose-built, cost-free mechanism that routes traffic from a private subnet directly to S3 over the AWS private network without traversing the public internet — no NAT Gateway is needed. Crucially, a Gateway endpoint supports an endpoint policy, which is an IAM resource-based policy attached to the endpoint itself. This endpoint policy can be scoped to a specific S3 bucket ARN (e.g., 'arn:aws:s3:::my-bucket' and 'arn:aws:s3:::my-bucket/*'), satisfying the requirement to restrict access to only that bucket. The private subnet's route table must also be updated to direct S3-destined traffic (prefix list) through the endpoint. Option A is incorrect because routing traffic through a NAT Gateway sends it over the public internet to S3, violating the 'no public internet' requirement; additionally, S3 bucket policies cannot reliably restrict access by NAT Gateway EIP since traffic appears as originating from that IP but the route is still public. Option C is partially valid (Interface endpoints also keep traffic off the internet) but Gateway endpoints are the standard AWS-recommended and cost-optimized choice for S3; furthermore, the question asks for the combination that 'satisfies both requirements' most precisely, and Gateway endpoint policies are the standard control plane for bucket-scoped endpoint restrictions. Option D is incorrect because S3 Transfer Acceleration uses CloudFront edge locations and routes over the internet — it does not keep traffic on the private AWS backbone within the VPC. Option E is incorrect because routing through a public-subnet proxy inherently introduces internet exposure and adds operational overhead, failing the 'no public internet' requirement.$patch$, $patch$Design Secure Architectures$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/privatelink/vpc-endpoints-s3.html","label":"AWS VPC Endpoints – Gateway Endpoints for Amazon S3"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/privatelink/vpc-endpoints-access.html","label":"AWS VPC Endpoint Policies"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/example-bucket-policies-vpc-endpoint.html","label":"AWS Documentation – Control access to VPC endpoints using endpoint policies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SAA-C03-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A solutions architect is designing a data processing pipeline where an EC2 instance in a private subnet must read objects from an Amazon S3 bucket. The security team requires that no S3 traffic traverse the public internet and that all access be restricted to only this specific S3 bucket. Which combination of actions satisfies these requirements? (Select ONE)$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A media company stores large video files in Amazon S3. Files are frequently accessed for the first 30 days after upload, rarely accessed between 31 and 90 days, and almost never accessed after 90 days. The company wants to minimize storage costs while ensuring files are retained indefinitely. Which combination of S3 storage classes should be used in a lifecycle policy to achieve the MOST cost-effective solution?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Keep in S3 Standard for 30 days → transition to S3 Standard-IA at 31 days → transition to S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval at 90 days"},{"id":"b","text":"Keep in S3 Standard for 30 days → transition to S3 Intelligent-Tiering at 31 days → transition to S3 Glacier Deep Archive at 90 days"},{"id":"c","text":"Keep in S3 Standard for 30 days → transition to S3 One Zone-IA at 31 days → transition to S3 Glacier Deep Archive at 90 days"},{"id":"d","text":"Keep in S3 Standard for 90 days → transition to S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval at 91 days"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that S3 Standard-IA is designed for infrequent access with a 30-day minimum storage duration, making it appropriate for objects that are rarely accessed after the first 30 days. S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval (90-day minimum) is one of the lowest-cost tiers for long-term archival of objects that are almost never accessed, satisfying the indefinite retention requirement at minimal cost. Option (a) therefore aligns each access phase with the most cost-effective storage class.

Option (b) is sub-optimal because S3 Intelligent-Tiering adds a per-object monitoring fee and is designed for unpredictable access patterns — the company's access pattern is well-defined, so Intelligent-Tiering adds unnecessary cost overhead.

Option (c) uses S3 One Zone-IA, which stores data in only one Availability Zone and introduces durability risk for valuable media assets; while slightly cheaper than Standard-IA, the reduced durability is generally not recommended for primary storage of irreplaceable files.

Option (d) ignores the cost savings available in the 31–90 day window entirely, keeping objects in S3 Standard when they could be in the cheaper Standard-IA tier, and Glacier Instant Retrieval (90-day minimum) is more expensive than Glacier Flexible Retrieval for data that is almost never accessed.$patch$, $patch$Design Cost-Optimized Architectures$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/storage-class-intro.html","label":"Amazon S3 Storage Classes Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/lifecycle-transition-general-considerations.html","label":"Amazon S3 Lifecycle Transitions and Expiration"},{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/s3/pricing/","label":"Amazon S3 Pricing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'SAA-C03-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A media company stores large video files in Amazon S3. Files are frequently accessed for the first 30 days after upload, rarely accessed between 31 and 90 days, and almost never accessed after 90 days. The company wants to minimize storage costs while ensuring files are retained indefinitely. Which combination of S3 storage classes should be used in a lifecycle policy to achieve the MOST cost-effective solution?$patch$);

